node.text:
Here’s the full 7 min film I was featured in for @dior ‘s Tales of the Wild series. Instagram doesn’t change your video orientation so just flip that phone sideways! 

I couldn’t be happier with how this turned out and I really appreciate that the directors let’s me talk about why I love bears and how they bring so much to the wilderness. They did an amazing job capturing those feelings as well as some great and unexpected bear interactions. The film is really beautiful and if you have a few minutes to watch it I’d love to hear what you think. 

Series by @clembeauvais and @arthur.de.k 
Directed by @clembeauvais 
Captured by @mackayvalentine

node.text:
Did a two day trip to Glacier/NW Montana and saw 6 grizzlies and 4 black bears. This one on a late evening might have been the highlight though. 

This time of year the bears in the area are focused in on berries and you can find them in big berry patches late in the evening or early in the morning. I’ve got my hot spots in the park and almost always find a bear or two. Took these photos from a safe distance with a long telephoto lens.

node.text: Today is Arctic Sea Ice Day and the Arctic and the Arctic sea ice are incredibly important to me personally, and to humanity as a whole. The Arctic is warming three times faster than the rest of the planet and as it does we are shortening the window of time of Arctic annual sea ice coverage, and we are quickly losing the multi-year ice that historically has persisted even through summers. Not only are polar bears and many other types of Arctic wildlife losing their habitat, but we are losing a powerful cooling force for the planet. Check out my stories to learn a bit more about what is happening in the Arctic and follow @polarbearsinternational for more information about how it affects polar bears. Also if you’re on Twitter follow Zack Labe for some really incredible and insightful graphs and statistics on sea ice cover.

node.text:
Yesterday I was able to return with  Dr. Markus Mika ( @aegolius14 ) to his flammulated owl project in northern Utah and weigh and band some tiny flamm nestlings and their moms. These little birds live in forests from BC all the way down to southern Mexico, and Dr. Mika has been working with them throughout his entire career. His research is shedding light on the types of prey these owls prefer, and how periods of drought or other climate change-induced issues affect prey availability and the owls that depend on that prey. Really fascinating research and we’ve got a new candidate on my ever-growing list of favorite birds. 

All birds were handled with the appropriate state and federal permits and under Dr. Mika’s care

node.text:
I got to assist the @hawkwatch kestrel team with some American kestrel nestling banding today. Kestrels are our smallest falcon and are vulnerable to a lot of different threats like rodenticide and habitat loss, and Hawkwatch has been running their kestrel monitoring project for years to assess those threats and come up with solutions. It’s also a project that relies on a lot of help from volunteers in the community, which is really great! 
Thanks for the invite @jennifer.bridge.2 

All birds were banded with the proper permits and training
